
@node Hotkeys, Screen Saver, Mixed, Mixed
@section Hotkeys

You can store up to 10 settings of the CoreOption (flame, display,
palette, ...) to hotkeys. 


To save the current setting press @code{h} (a message will appear on the
bottom of the screen) and then a number key. When using @code{xcthugha}
you can also use Shift + Number instead.

To restore the settings from the hotkeys, just press @code{0}, @code{1},
... @code{9}.


The values for the hotkeys are saved in
@code{~/.cthugha.auto} when you press @code{a}.




@node Screen Saver, Pathes, Hotkeys, Mixed
@section Screen Saver

I have removed the "native" screen saver support of @code{xcthugha}. So
you must use a program like @code{xscreensaver} 
@footnote{see @code{http://people.netscape.com/jwz/xscreensaver}}. 

You should specify the options @code{--root} and @code{--verbose=-1}.
The first will force @code{xcthugha} to draw onto the root window, the
second will suppress most text displayed.
So an entry for the resource database for @code{xcthugha} will look like

@example
   xscreensaver.programs: xcthugha --root --verbose=-1
@end example


Of course you can also add extra arguments to @code{xcthugha} as you need them.
For example @code{--zoom 1} to prevent @code{xcthugha} from filling the
whole screen.








@node Pathes, Other OS, Screen Saver, Mixed

@section Pathes

Cthugha will search in the following directories for translation tables,
palette files and pcx images:

@enumerate
@item Current directory for all 3 kinds of files
@item @code{./tab}, @code{./map} and @code{./pcx}
@item In @code{@value{INSTLIB}/tab/BUFF_WIDTHxBUFF_HEIGHT} for
translation tables
@item @code{@value{INSTLIB}/tab}, @*
@code{@value{INSTLIB}/map} and @*
@code{@value{INSTLIB}/pcx}
@item @code{LIB_DIR/tab}, @code{LIB_DIR/map} and @code{LIB_DIR/pcx}.
Where @code{LIB_DIR} is specified by the parameter @code{--path} and
BUFF_WIDTHxBUFF_HEIGHT is the size of the buffer in dezimal (e.g. 320x200).
@end enumerate











@node Other OS, Rules, Pathes, Mixed
@section Other Operating Systems

You can find the other versions at the official Cthugha home page
@code{http://www.afn.org/cthugha}.

@itemize @bullet

@item other @strong{unix} systems.

@code{xcthugha} should also work on non-Linux machines, but several
things will not work. Sound reading is probably the most important thing
that will not work (maybe something like @code{--play /dev/audio --silent}
works).


@item @strong{DOS} - Cthugha V5.1 and V5.3

This version of Cthugha-L is based on cthugha V5.1 and V5.3 by
Kevin Burfitt. Most things 
from the DOS-version work exactly the same way in the Linux-Version. 
Cthugha-L has a lot of additional features.


@item @strong{PowerMac} - MaCthugha

Rus Maxham (@code{rus@@interstice.com}) has done a port of Cthugha for the
PowerMac.


@item @strong{xf86cthugha}.

A special version of Cthugha-L supporting DGA
(Direct Graphics Access) with XFree86. 
Mark Vojkovich (@code{mvojkov@@ucsd.edu}) has done this version. You
can also find it at @code{ftp.afn.org} or via the WWW page. 

I included DGA support in some version, but I dropped it -- it only
makes problems (especially with fonts) and is not even faster.


@item @strong{Win95}.

Kevin Burfitt (@code{zaph@@torps.apana.org.au}) is currently working on a
new version of Cthugha for Windows 95. 


@item @strong{BeOS}.

There will (soon) be a version of Cthugha for BeOS.
Raphael Moll (@code{<raphael.moll@@capway.com>})
is working on this.

@end itemize












@node Rules, Press, Other OS, Mixed
@section Rules

So you want to add/modify the source code, just follow this simple rules.

@table @emph
@item Rule #1:
Go for it!!!  This is a free project - make it big! 

@item Rule #2:
Send me some Email telling me which bits you are playing with, 
and I will keep you up to date if I (or anyone else) make any 
major changes to the code. 

@item Rule #3:  
Put your name/email address in the code/credits, that way you get to 
share the fame :-) 

@item Rule #4:  
There is no Rule #4

@item Rule #5:
@emph{Please} keep me up to date, with any little functions or ideas 
you have... The program is evolving quickly, and I'd love to 
incorporate your ideas! 

@item Rule #6:  
Translation tables: 
If you design a weird and wonderful translation table, send 
me either the table or (even better) the code used to generate it! 

@item Rule #7: 
Don't Panic


@end table












